body_text.text:
The development of chronic lung allograft rejection (CLAD
), encountered as bronchiolitis obliterans syndrome ( BOS) or restrictive chronic lung allograft dysfunction (R-CLAD)
, continues to be the primary driver of mortality in LTR after the first 2 years following transplantation. Obliterative bronchiolitis, the hallmark of BOS, appears to be the pathologic end-stage of a process initially beginning with airway epithelial injury and leading to inflammatory reactions that promote airway obliteration. The inciting injury to the epithelium may be initiated as an exposure to toxic chemicals or drugs, infection including to viral agents, or an autoimmune process [3, 29, 30]. Airway inflammation and injury resulting from both the number and severity of episodes of acute rejection are also thought to play an important role in the development of CLAD [3, 30].
